Q taken

A consumer purchases a smartphone worth ₹85,000 from an online e-commerce platform during a festive sale. The product listing states that the phone is “brand new, factory sealed, with 1-year manufacturer warranty.”

After delivery:

The consumer discovers that the phone was previously activated, has battery health degradation, and shows signs of prior use.

The seller refuses replacement, claiming the product passed “quality checks.”

The e-commerce platform denies liability, stating it is only an intermediary.

The manufacturer refuses warranty coverage, alleging the device was sold by an unauthorized seller.

The consumer later finds that multiple complaints exist online against the same seller for similar practices.

The consumer files a complaint before the District Consumer Disputes Redressal Commission, seeking:

Full refund

Compensation for mental harassment

Punitive damages against the seller and the platform

The e-commerce platform argues:

The complaint is not maintainable due to an arbitration clause in its user agreement.

No “deficiency in service” on its part.

Liability, if any, lies solely with the seller.

Question:

What constitutional, statutory, and procedural issues must the Consumer Commission consider while deciding:

Whether the complainant qualifies as a “consumer” under the Consumer Protection Act, 2019

Whether selling a previously used product as “new” amounts to deficiency in service and unfair trade practice

The extent of liability of the seller, e-commerce platform, and manufacturer

The effect of the arbitration clause on the maintainability of the consumer complaint

The scope of compensation and punitive damages that may be awarded


Q1
When exactly did you purchase the smartphone that was sold to you as new?
answer-I purchased the smartphone on **10 October 2025** through the e-commerce platform during its festive sale, and it was delivered to me on **14 October 2025**.



