Question 2Q of 5

What are the exact terms of the warranty that were provided to you by the seller or the manufacturer at the time of purchase, and are they mentioned in any documentation such as the bill or warranty card?

answer-At the time of purchase, the product listing and invoice clearly stated that the smartphone was covered by a **one-year manufacturer warranty** applicable from the date of activation, with no exclusions disclosed regarding the seller’s authorization status. This warranty assurance was reflected on the **tax invoice** issued by the seller and in the **digital warranty information** accompanying the product, while no separate warranty card or document mentioned any limitation, disclaimer, or condition that would exclude warranty coverage due to the seller being unauthorized.


3Q-
Can you provide the specific provisions of the arbitration clause in the e-commerce platform's user agreement that you agreed to at the time of purchase, particularly any details regarding the dispute resolution process and the applicable laws governing such disputes?

answer-The e-commerce platform’s user agreement contains a standard **arbitration clause** stating that any dispute arising out of or relating to purchases made on the platform shall be resolved through **binding arbitration**, to be conducted by a **sole arbitrator appointed by the platform**, with the **seat and venue of arbitration in India**. The clause specifies that the arbitration proceedings shall be governed by the **Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996**, and that Indian law shall be the applicable law, while also stating that users waive their right to pursue disputes before civil courts, without expressly mentioning or excluding remedies available under the **Consumer Protection Act, 2019**.


4Q-
What details of quality checks, if any, were performed by the seller on the smartphone before it was shipped to you, and is there any documentation or certification provided with the device that verifies its condition as new at the time of sale?

answer-The seller has merely asserted that the smartphone passed internal “quality checks” prior to shipment but has **not disclosed the nature, parameters, or methodology** of such checks. No **quality assurance report, inspection certificate, refurbishment disclosure, or third-party verification document** was provided with the device to certify its condition as new. Apart from the generic invoice and packaging, there is **no documentary material** accompanying the smartphone that verifies it was unused or factory sealed at the time of sale.

5Q-


Have you had any previous interactions or communications with the seller or the e-commerce platform regarding the issue of the smartphone being sold as new, and if so, can you provide the details of those interactions, including dates and the specific concerns or issues you raised?
Yes. After discovering that the smartphone showed signs of prior activation and use, I contacted the seller through the e-commerce platform’s customer support system on **16 October 2025**, raising concerns that the device was not new as advertised and requesting a replacement or refund. The seller responded on **18 October 2025**, stating that the product had cleared quality checks and denying any defect. I then escalated the issue to the platform’s customer support on **20 October 2025**, providing photographs and screenshots showing prior activation details and battery health information; however, on **22 October 2025**, the platform rejected my complaint, stating that it could not intervene in disputes between buyers and third-party sellers.





